          The article concludes that these actions are entrenched in the colonial logic of capitalism, forcing traditional communities, especially Black ones, to sacrifice their lands and ways of life in the name of economic progress. These practices exemplify environmental racism, not necessarily through explicit discriminatory intent but through their racialized impacts.
          In summary, the text critiques how these sectors, often justified as engines of development and job creation, impose significant environmental and social costs on quilombola communities, exacerbating the historical inequality and marginalization of these groups.
          
